On Saturday I ventured into the wonderful world of pizza delivery.

Actually, it wasn't too bad.  It was actually kind of fun.  It was followed by what I hear was the busiest Sunday night the store has seen in years.  I made lots of money, but it wasn't so much fun as "OMFG make it stop!"

I got lost trying to find a house on Dixon Road in Culpeper.  Apparently the house I was looking for had a big pond out front and a garage to the side.  Since that part of town is allergic to streetlights, I would have been lucky to brake if a herd of cattle had been wandering across the road.

We have almost ... but not quite ... made rent.  It was due no later than the 5th of the month, but we weren't even close.  We got some help from the church, in the form of a check, which I deposited in my bank account on Monday ... not realizing that Monday was a holiday for anybody who works for the government or a bank.  The check has not yet cleared but should be through by tomorrow morning.

I spent a good part of today learning exactly how many ways my bank has to say, "There's not a damn thing we can do about your deposit, and we're not going to allow you to overdraw your account to buy money orders to pay rent, and we really, really don't care if you could get evicted over this.  It's not our problem."

That's okay, they won't be my bank for much longer.

And for my next trick, my latest crop of bills exceeds my pay from AHC.  Fortunately, there's more money coming in now, and it should all balance out.

I have an awesome (practically awe-inspiring) family, and as rough as things are now, I know things are getting better.  I just don't want another month like this for a very long time.

When I was a high school student, I lived a few blocks from several convenience stores.  In Michigan, they're called "party stores."  This is presumably because it's where you go when you want to buy stuff so you can go party.  (It did cause some confusion when I moved to Virginia, where a party store is where you buy banners and balloons.)

The party store I usually went to was caled Hollywood Market.  Hollywood was actually a block or two away from Hollywood Drive, which is the wealthiest neighborhood in downtown Monroe.

Hollywood Market offered pretty much every vice legally available in my hometown at that time. Caffeine?  Coffee, Coke, Mountain Dew.  Munchies?  Sweet or salty, pretty much anything you wanted.  Beer, wine, hard liquor.  Cigarettes, cigars, chewing tobacco.

When my friends and I got together, it was pretty standard that we would take along some alcoholic beverage with us.  Sometimes Paul would get one of his older brothers to buy for us, or Jim (not me, another Jim) would raid his mom's liquor cabinet or steal or otherwise aqcuire a bottle somewhere.

Yeah, the legal drinking age was 21, but determination, money and connections tend to override such trivia.

Hollywood had two cash registers, and the same people were usually running them, a guy on the left and a woman on the right.  They were both in their mid-twenties, and I think they were both related to the store's owners.

One night I came in and it wasn't busy, so I started talking to the guy at his register, not about anything in particular, just shooting the breeze, and I mentioned something about high school.

"Oh, seriously?" he said.  "Wow, I thought you were about my age."

As soon as he said that, I realized that, at any time prior to my having said that, this guy probably would have sold me hard liquor without carding me.  However, now that I'd blurted this out, there was no chance.

A few days went by, and I came in on another slow night, only this time I was talking to the woman at the other register, just shooting the breeze, and ... again.

"Oh, seriously?" she said.  "Wow, I thought you were about my age."

I do remember laughing and shaking my head a lot as I walked home that night.
It's really not a big deal.

My computer, which used to be able to run Sims 2 and other processor-intensive games and apps for hours on end has been very erratic lately.  In the interest of fixing this, I bought a new video card, replaced the soundcard, reformatted several times, moved the cards around in the slots to make sure that they were properly ventillated, but to no avail:  I'd run Sims 2 (or a Tycoon game, or something else) for maybe fifteen minutes, and the whole machine would just freeze up.

So tonight, I asked for advice from the guy who had built the machine in the first place, and he suggested blowing out the inside of the machine with canned air, because it sounded to him like it was overheating.  Tommie, my roommate, went a step forther, and suggested that I take the fan off the heat sink that sits on top of the CPU.

And I found a goat.

Okay, not an *entire* goat, just what looked like most of its fur.

I don't think the fan has been moved since the machine was built four years ago; there was this huge accumulation of crud under the fan itself, most of which I was able to remove.

I'm no longer wondering why my computer crapped out on the heavy games; but I am marveling a bit that the sucker ran as well as it did.

Nikki has announced that she's going to be here (not to visit, to live) before June. She's talked to a few people here in Reno about jobs, and Long's (one of the local drug-store chains) told her that there was an 80-90% chance that she'd get hired, based on her qualifications and experience. I also have a friend who works in the pharmacy at the University of Nevada (Reno), who might be able to get Nikki in there ... which would mean a non-retail job. Always a good thing. Also, I ordered my Telecaster last night. (Yes, I upgraded. If I only buy one guitar, then damn it, it's going to be a good one.) I'll have it early next week. And my (late) New Year's resolution is to learn how to play it well enough to justify the money I spent on it. The package that I bought will allow me to record straight to the computer, and I even got a mic with a stand, so I hope to have something musical and guitar-based online in the near future. I actually do play a little guitar already ... I took lessons when I was a teenager. It's just a matter of re-learning the scales and chords, and building up callouses on my left hand. So, yeah ... things are looking very good.

Test finished!
you chose BY - your Enneagram type is FOUR.

"I am unique"

Romantics have sensitive feelings and are warm and perceptive.

How to Get Along with Me

  • Give me plenty of compliments. They mean a lot to me.
  • Be a supportive friend or partner. Help me to learn to love and value myself.
  • Respect me for my special gifts of intuition and vision.
  • Though I don't always want to be cheered up when I'm feeling melancholy, I sometimes like to have someone lighten me up a little.
  • Don't tell me I'm too sensitive or that I'm overreacting!

What I Like About Being a Four

  • my ability to find meaning in life and to experience feeling at a deep level
  • my ability to establish warm connections with people
  • admiring what is noble, truthful, and beautiful in life
  • my creativity, intuition, and sense of humor
  • being unique and being seen as unique by others
  • having aesthetic sensibilities
  • being able to easily pick up the feelings of people around me

What's Hard About Being a Four

  • experiencing dark moods of emptiness and despair
  • feelings of self-hatred and shame; believing I don't deserve to be loved
  • feeling guilty when I disappoint people
  • feeling hurt or attacked when someone misundertands me
  • expecting too much from myself and life
  • fearing being abandoned
  • obsessing over resentments
  • longing for what I don't have

Fours as Children Often

  • have active imaginations: play creatively alone or organize playmates in original game s
  • are very sensitive
  • feel that they don't fit in
  • believe they are missing something that other people have
  • attach themselves to idealized teachers, heroes, artists, etc.
  • become antiauthoritarian or rebellious when criticized or not understood
  • feel lonely or abandoned (perhaps as a result of a death or their parents' divorce)

Fours as Parents

  • help their children become who they really are
  • support their children's creativity and originality
  • are good at helping their children get in touch with their feelings
  • are sometimes overly critical or overly protective
  • are usually very good with children if not too self-absorbed

Renee Baron & Elizabeth Wagele

The Enneagram Made Easy
Discover the 9 Types of People
HarperSanFrancisco, 1994, 161 pages

I was getting ready to go shopping on Saturday afternoon and I decided to check my bank balance before I left ... and noticed that someone had recently charged almost $300 to my credit card to a Paypal account. I may be a little absent-minded sometimes, but that seems like the sort of thing I'd remember, right? So, feeling very stressed, I called my bank and asked them if they could stop it from posting, and they basically said, "No, but we can look into in on Wednesday." So, still feeling stressed, I contacted Paypal today. Apparently, somebody set up a Yahoo email account on the same day that this transaction was made. And aparently, they were buying something from here. So. The merchant thought that the purchase looked suspicious and credited it back to my account, and I should have the money back in a few days. I love having my credit card number stolen by random drug dealers.

7-11 has been marketing its onw brand of sodas for a while now, and I've gotten hooked on Apple Gingersnap ... basically, apple juice and ginger ale combined.  It's pretty tasty.

I got my TV and new VCR/DVD player hooked up to my digital cable box, so I now have a bazillion channels available to me in addition to the ability to watch everything I own on DVD or VHS.  So naturally, I spent the entire weekend watching bad movies on Sci-Fi.

Okay, not the ENTIRE weekend.  Before I fell asleep last night, I watched an episode of South of Nowhere ... I like that they're doing the unconventional-relationship thing, but they REALLY need to hire a better team of scriptwriters. Preferrably with something resembling a sense of humor.  They don't have to go balls-out comedy, but come on ... a little comic relief once in a while goes a long way.

I'm still stewing on the novel.  I'm going to finish in in a burst of creativity lasting a week or two, whenever that kicks in ... because that's how I write.  I'm a sprinter.  My average weekly output sucks, but when I'm focused and inspirted, it just comes rolling out.  I've recognized what I'm trying to say with the story, and gotten my head around where it's going to end; I'm a little worried that it's going to come across as kind of blah, not very original, nothing earth-shattering; but I'm not trying to write timeless prose, here, I'm not trying to say something that has never been said before.  I'm just presenting what is essentially a romance, the story of a relationship between a guy and a girl, and his realization that life is messy, life is random, and he really wouldn't want it to be any other way.  Call it an ode to chaos, if you will.  All the planning in the world can get you to where you think you want to go, but it's the things that happen that you can't control that, in the end, define who you are.
